    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>As <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/a/59806366/139985\">@Miles</a> explains, the JIT compiler can generate code that uses <code>divmod</code> instructions where appropriate.</p>\n<p>So I want to address these aspects of the question.</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Does java have a divmod instruction?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>No.  Plainly no.  (See below for <em>some</em> reasons why.)</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I want to use it because it usually is more readable in writing out above types of algorithms. I expect it to be there because it is more natural for the CPU.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>So I guess you would like to be able to write something like this in Java:</p>\n<pre><code>q, r = x divmod y;  // where divmod is a hypothetical operator\n</code></pre>\n<p>or</p>\n<pre><code>q, r = Math.divmod(x, y);\n</code></pre>\n<p>See the problems?</p>\n<ul>\n<li><p>Java doesn't support returning more than one value from a method call.  At a pretty fundamental level.  This is not just a syntactic  thing: the JVM spec doesn't support it!</p>\n</li>\n<li><p>Unlike Python, Java doesn't have a multi-assignment syntax.</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Maybe we could implement <code>divmod</code> like this:</p>\n<pre><code>double[] dm = Math.divmod(x, y);\n// dm[0] is q and dm[1] is r\n</code></pre>\n<p>This is analogous to how <code>BigDecimal.divideAndRemainder(BigDecimal)</code> works. But now we have new issues:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>The <code>divmod</code> method (or operator) is allocating an array</li>\n<li>Retrieving the quotient or remainder involves subscripting an array.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>(There would be a lot of scope for JIT optimization to reduce the above overheads.  But not in all cases.)</p>\n<ol start=\"3\">\n<li>We have lost the (supposed) readability benefit of introducing <code>divmod</code>.</li>\n</ol>\n"
  } ],
